'''Einstein Gravity in a Nutshell''' is a [[textbook]] by [[Anthony Zee]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/820123453|title=Einstein gravity in a nutshell|last=A.|first=Zee,|isbn=9780691145587|location=Princeton|oclc=820123453}}</ref>
== Response == Michael Berg said in a review in the [[Mathematical Association of America]], "I must admit that, as its [[Quantum Field Theory in a nutshell|nutshell predecessor]], ''Einstein Gravity in a Nutshell'' is very appealing to me, and I am certainly won over by Zee’s chatty but on-the-money style".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.maa.org/press/maa-reviews/einstein-gravity-in-a-nutshell|title=Einstein Gravity in a Nutshell {{!}} Mathematical Association of America|website=www.maa.org|access-date=2017-10-04}}</ref> [[Luboš Motl]] said about the book on his blog ''The Reference Frame'': "Anthony is more playful and less formal but there are aspects in which he gets further than any other introductory textbook of GR. The book is full of notes, a long index, and simply clever exercises. The illustrations are pretty and professional [...] I recommend you once again to try the book".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://motls.blogspot.com/2013/05/anthony-zee-einstein-gravity-in-nutshell.html|title=Anthony Zee: Einstein Gravity in a Nutshell|website=The Reference Frame|access-date=2017-10-04}}</ref> [[Pedro G. Ferreira]], professor at the [[University of Oxford]] called it "a remarkably complete and thorough textbook on general relativity, written in a refreshing and engaging style. Zee leads us through all the major intellectual steps that make what is surely one of the most profound and beautiful theories of all time. The book is enjoyable and informative in equal measure. Quite an achievement."<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://press.princeton.edu/titles/10038.html|title=Einstein Gravity in a Nutshell|website=Princeton University Press|language=en|access-date=2017-10-05}}</ref>
